Exercises

Tools for the Exercise

  • Basic Exercises

    • FIJI (ImageJ with all the plugins already installed): Visualization, Preprocessing, Segmentation, Morphometrics [http://www.fiji.sc]
    • Matlab (General Processing, Image Processing Toolbox) [http://www.mathworks.com]
    • MIJI (Interface betweeen Matlab and ImageJ) [http://bigwww.epfl.ch/sage/soft/mij/]

  • Advanced Exercises

    • Visualizing Structures in Paraview
    • K-Means in Paraview
    • Loading Data into R

Objectives (Advanced in Italics)

  1. Compare different samples using

    • Nearest Neighbor Distance
    • Delaunay Neighbors
    • Territory
    • Distribution Tensor
    • Alignment Tensor

  2. Find layers in a sample using

    • shape
    • local density
    • orientation

  3. Determine which process happened between two sample groups

  4. Visualize Tensor Data

  5. Visualize Layers in 3D

Setting up the Computers

Once you have logged in

  1. Open Matlab
  2. Type in the following commands exactly!
  3. This will start Fiji

Setting up the Computers

In Matlab run the following code Copy / Paste from Here

cd('~')
unzip('http://jenkins.imagej.net/job/Stable-Fiji/lastSuccessfulBuild/artifact/fiji-nojre.zip','./')

addpath 'Fiji.app/scripts'
Miji % start Miji
cd('~')
% to test if it works
% Miji_Test

Changing Java Heap

If the Java Heap Space is not high enough strange error messages may appear. Increase the Java Heap Space using the preferences (in this movie)

Basic MIJ (MIJ) Refresher

Tools provide an interface between Matlab and FIJI

Pushing Matlab Images to ImageJ

% random 500 x 500 array
imData=rand(500); 
MIJ.createImage('test',imData,true);

Reading Images from FIJI to Matlab

MIJ.run('Embryos (42K)');
imData = MIJ.getCurrentImage;
% take the sum of red, green, and blue
imSum = sum(double(imData(:,:,1)),3); 
subplot(1,2,1)
imagesc(imSum);
subplot(1,2,2);
imagesc(imSum<150)

Comparing Samples

Each of these samples was measured from a different treatment group, calculate general statistics about the same and try and determine what transformation was applied from the normal (sample-a) to get to this point. Comparing histograms of nearest neighbor positions might be a good starting point.

Layer Problems

For the layer problems

  • load the CSV (comma separated value) text files in Matlab
  • use and modify the given scripts
    • to identify how many different layers are present in the system
    • how they are oriented
    • how thick they are.

For some samples this is easier than others, the sample scripts just use one or two parameters, try using more to do the K-means analysis.

  • we use 2 as the default number of layers what happens when this value is increased?

Classifying Cells

  • Starting Script

You can either use your own output or the one (https://github.com/kmader/Quantitative-Big-Imaging-Course/blob/master/Ex7/analyzeParticlesOutput.txt) located in the course directory along with the sample script. To classify cells into groups, right now we just use nearest neighbor distance and area, how does adding additional parameters change the result

Challenge: 3D analysis

3D data analyzed with Matlab or in ImageJ using the 3D Object Analyzer function can also be analyzed using similar scripts. Modify the scripts so it can display the data and run k-means. Modify findnn.m to find the nearest neighbor in 3D

Alignment

  • Starting Script
  • Which of the two samples are more aligned? Why?

  • Can you find a method for calculating the alignment more appropriately for the second sample?

Advanced: Paraview

  • What is ParaView
    • parallel, distributed image processing and visualization toolbox written in C++
    • open source, extendable API
    • pipeline style analyses

Creating a state

With the test file

pvpython ViewShape.py -c test3d.csv -t -s test3dState.pvsm

With your own files from Matlab or FIJI

pvpython ViewShape.py -c analyzeParticlesOutput.txt -x X -y Y -z Mean -s teststate.pvsm --tab
